      "title": "Chapter 1: Fluid Mechanics & Hydraulics",
      "sections": [
        {
          "type": "table",
          "level": 3,
          "title": "Fluid Mechanics & Hydraulics - Core Concepts",
          "table": {
            "header": ["SUB-TOPIC", "SHORT DESCRIPTION / NOTES / KEY FORMULAS", "EXTRA"],
            "rows": [
              [
                "PHYSICAL PROPERTIES OF FLUID",
                "• Density ρ = Mass/Volume (kg/m³)\n• Specific Weight γ = ρ × g (N/m³)\n• Specific Gravity σ = ρ/ρ_water\n• Viscosity μ – Resistance to flow (N·s/m²); Kinematic viscosity ν = μ/ρ (m²/s)\n• Surface Tension σ – Force per unit length (N/m)\n• Capillary Rise h = (4σ cos θ)/(ρ g r)",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "PRESSURE AND PASCAL'S LAW",
                "• Pressure p = Force/Area (N/m²)\n• Pascal's Law: Pressure applied to confined fluid is transmitted equally in all directions.\n• Gauge Pressure = Absolute – Atmospheric Pressure\n• Pressure Head h = p/(ρg)",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "HYDROSTATIC PRESSURE ON PLANE SURFACES",
                "• Pressure varies linearly with depth: p = ρgh\n• Total Pressure P = ρg ħ A\n• Center of Pressure h_cp = ħ + (IG sin²θ)/(ħA)",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "BUOYANCY AND STABILITY OF FLOATING BODIES",
                "• Archimedes' Principle: Upthrust = Weight of displaced fluid\n• Condition for floatation: W = ρgV_displaced\n• Metacentric Height GM = BM - BG; for stable equilibrium, GM > 0\n• BM = I/V (I = Moment of inertia of waterline area, V = displaced volume)",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "FLUID KINEMATICS",
                "• Studies motion of fluid without forces.\n• Types of Flow: Steady/Unsteady, Uniform/Non-uniform, Laminar/Turbulent, Compressible/Incompressible.\n• Continuity Equation: Q = A₁V₁ = A₂V₂\n• Streamline – tangent to velocity; Pathline – actual path; Streakline – locus of successive particles.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "FLUID DYNAMICS",
                "• Euler's Equation: (dp/ρg) + (dv²/2g) + dz = 0\n• Bernoulli's Equation: (p/ρg) + (v²/2g) + z = constant\n• Head Loss (Darcy–Weisbach): h_f = f (L/D) (V²/2g)\n• Power through pipe: P = ρgQH\n• Hydraulic gradient line (HGL) and Total energy line (TEL) used for flow energy visualization.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "NAVIER-STOKES EQUATION",
                "Represents motion of viscous fluids (momentum balance).\nGeneral form: ρ (du/dt) = ρg - ∇p + μ∇²u",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "BOUNDARY LAYER THEORY",
                "• Thin layer near a boundary where viscous effects dominate.\n• Boundary layer thickness (δ): Distance from wall where V = 0.99 V_∞\n• Reynolds number: Re = ρVD/μ (Re < 2300 → Laminar, Re > 4000 → Turbulent)\n• Flow separation occurs if adverse pressure gradient develops.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "MOMENTUM EQUATION",
                "From Newton's 2nd Law: ΣF = ρQ(V₂ - V₁)\nUsed to calculate forces on pipe bends, nozzles, and vanes.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "OPEN CHANNEL FLOW – BASICS",
                "Flow with a free surface under gravity.\nFlow Types: Steady/Unsteady, Uniform/Non-uniform, Laminar/Turbulent, Subcritical/Supercritical.\nFroude Number (Fr) = V/√(gD) → Fr < 1: Subcritical, Fr = 1: Critical, Fr > 1: Supercritical.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "UNIFORM FLOW (CHEZY & MANNING FORMULAS)",
                "• Chezy Formula: V = C√(RS)\n• Manning Formula: V = (1/n) R^(2/3) S^(1/2)\nWhere R = A/P (Hydraulic radius), S = slope, n = Manning's coefficient.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "ENERGY & MOMENTUM PRINCIPLES IN CHANNEL FLOW",
                "• Specific Energy (E): E = y + (V²/2g)\n• Critical Depth (y_c): Occurs when E is minimum for a given Q → y_c = (q²/g)^(1/3), q = Q/b\n• Specific Force (F): F = Q²/gA + Aȳ",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "FLOW OVER NOTCHES & WEIRS",
                "• Rectangular Notch: Q = (2/3) C_d √(2g) b H^(3/2)\n• Triangular (V) Notch: Q = (8/15) C_d √(2g) tan(θ/2) H^(5/2)\n• Cipolletti Weir: Q = (2/3) C_d √(2g) b H^(3/2) (approx.)\n• Broad-crested weir: Q = C_d b h √(2gh)",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "GRADUALLY VARIED FLOW (GVF)",
                "Flow with gradual depth variation.\nDifferential Equation: dy/dx = (S₀ - S_f)/(1 - Fr²)\nProfile depends on bed slope (Mild, Steep, Critical, Horizontal, Adverse).",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "HYDRAULIC JUMP",
                "Rapid transition from supercritical to subcritical flow.\nSequent Depth Ratio: y₂/y₁ = ½[√(1 + 8Fr₁²) - 1]\nEnergy Loss: ΔE = ((y₂ - y₁)³)/(4y₁y₂)\nApplication: Energy dissipation below spillways.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "FLOW IN MOBILE BOUNDARY CHANNELS",
                "Occurs when bed and banks are erodible.\nRegime Channel Design (Lacey's Equations):\nV = (2/5) √f R^(2/3), P = 4.75 √Q, A = 2.5 Q/f^(1/3), S = 0.0003 f^(5/3)/Q^(1/6)\n(f = silt factor = 1.76 √d, where d = mean particle size in mm).",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "FLOW MEASUREMENT DEVICES",
                "• Venturimeter: Q = C_d A₂ √[2gh/(1 - (A₂/A₁)²)]\n• Orifice meter: Q = C_d a √(2gh)\n• Pitot tube: h = V²/(2g)\n• Weir/Notch: Flow measurement in open channels.",
                ""
              ]
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "formulas",
          "level": 3,
          "title": "Important Formulas – Fluid Mechanics & Hydraulics",
          "items": [
            { "name": "Continuity Equation", "expr": "Q = A₁V₁ = A₂V₂" },
